Glammaa
Canberra, Australia232 contributions
0
3.0 of 5 bubbles
Bitter sweet
May 2017 ‚Ä¢ Couples
This overnight cruise was booked as apart of our Vietnam tour through AsiaView. The company we did the cruise with was called Gray Line Halong Cruise.

After a gruelling 4.5 hour bus trip from Hanoi we reached the port where our boat Minh Hang was berthed. I was pleasantly surprised as I had read some terrible reviews and also heard via other travellers that the boats were dreadful. My first impressions were that the boat looked seaworthy and in pretty good condition.
We were taken onboard about 30minutes after arriving and were again nicely surprised. The dining area was air conditioned and set up really nicely.
Once we were given our safety brief we were given our room keys. Our guide was very happy to advise us that we had a VIP suite. Hmm i thought, we shall see. During our safety brief we were also advised that all prices were in American dollars which shocked us. The prices we had been told prior to the cruise were triple. Beer was still reasonable at USD$2.50 but cocktails were USD$6. We had been told that drinks on board were a little more expensive than local prices. Local priced beer is 60cents and a cocktail is anywhere from $1 - $1.50
It was lovely, a reasonably spacious room and bathroom and a private balcony which had two lounge chairs and 2 deck chairs. It also had pretty good aircondlting which for a woman in her early 50's is vital :)
Off we sailed with I kid you not about 200 similar boats, they were everywhere. The waterway pretty much resembled the chaotic streets of Hanoi complete with tooting boat horns.
All of our meals were pretty good, they could improve on their toast making skills but hey everything else was fine.
We did several tours off the boat which are all included in the price.
First tour, and you had two options. You could take a kayak or you could go on a local boat and view the caves. We chose to take the local boat but most of the youngsters chose to kayak and really enjoyed it. The cave is a cave and there are caves everywhere but it was nice being on the water and there was a lovely breeze. It took about an hour.
Tour two was to swim at a beach or you could choose to walk up 430 stairs to the top of the mountain Ti Top and view the islands. We chose the beach and the youngsters chose the hike.
The beach was a bitter disappointment. It was packed and I mean packed, i imagine from a distance it must have looked like a seal colony. From a distance the water looked so beautiful and we could not wait to get in. Up close the water was filthy and the beach is littered with rubbish. We waded in waist deep and then got out, it was like the filth clung to your skin. We were there again for about an hour.
Back on board we had about an hour "free time" and were advised that it was Happy Hour. Drinks were two for one, Yippee.
I had been told that drinks would be watered down so when I ordered my pi√±a coladas the barman said "Sit down I will bring them" and my response was "Oh no I would love to see how you make them".
This caused panic and it was decided that the manager should make my drinks. He grabbed a bottle of I have no idea what and I asked him what it was. Oh mam it is the rum for the drink, my response was Oh but pi√±a coladas are made from white rum not brown and Malibu. He very begrudgingly got the right booze and made the drinks with full nips whilst muttering in Vietnamese. When everyone ordered their drinks they did the same thing and watched the bar men make them. For this i received quite a few dark looks. Oh and the only drinks that are in the Happy Hour are cocktails.
The remainder of the evening was spent happily drinking beers on the deck and getting to know our fellow travellers.
Our bed was a bit firm however we slept well, this may or may not have been due to our booze consumption.
There was an option to rise early and do tai chi on the top deck at 6am, no one from our cruise participated. I suspect this was due to the amount of booze consumed the night before.
Breakfast was served early, 7am. Right after breakfast we were taken to another set of caves which were lovely. It is was bit of a steep climb but we were all grateful it was early as already it was hot.
We had to be out of our rooms by 930am and this gave us another hour of free time before brunch was served at 10:30.
After brunch we were given our bills for drinks and pretty much all hell broke loose. People had been charged USD$1.50 for water and tea and coffee that were offered after meals were also charged at USD$2 and $3 respectively. Then we noticed, as did everyone else that we had all been charged for our cocktails. As all of us only ordered 2 cocktails during the happy hour because of the cost and we turned to beer. When we queried the bill were we told that the Happy Hour meant when you purchased two cocktails the third one was free. Every single person on the boat got it wrong. To make matter worse the bills were only produced after people had completed their questionnaires about what they thought of the trip.
I can tell you there were not a lot of happy people. However they did give everyone a $2 discount. Me along with several other people advised that whilst they may have their surveys completed that the backlash on places such as Trip Advisor would be severe. This did not seem to bother them.
So, was the trip worthwhile and would I recommend it.
Here is some food for thought before you book.
It is a gruelling 4-5 hour bus trip from Hanoi each way. There is a comfort stop at one of the most expensive places we have been to in vietnam both there and back. The bus trip on the way there was bareable as the bus was somewhat comfortable. The return trip was hell. we had a different bus and it was tiny. We were all westerners and to try and get down the aisle of the bus was a really tight squeeze and two westerners to a seat meant we were packed in like sardines. Whilst the bus had air conditioning it had no suspension what so ever and we bounced around like pop corn under heat.
Halong Bay is filthy and if you have seen one cave with stalagmites and titles then you have seen them all.
Knowing what I know now, I would have spent the extra time in Hoi An. Think very hard about visiting Halong Bay.
Written May 28, 2017
This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC. Tripadvisor performs checks on reviews as part of our industry-leading trust & safety standards. Read our transparency report to learn more.
