Beautiful scenery, Very disappointing management and ecological practices
Mar 2017 ‚Ä¢ Friends
We visited Halong Bay in March, the weather was not on our side, it was cloudy and we didn't enjoy the scenery and sun as much as we hoped we would. Despite the spectacular view, the place is extremely dirty: rubbish and trash in the water everywhere, plastic bags, vodka & wine bottles, oil spills, dead fish floating on the surface of the water. Poor ecological practices, No one is taking care of the bay to clean up the mess of the nearly 500 touristic boats. We had a very strict program and were faced with unreasonable answers from the crew members and our guide. We were taken to a spot to kayak (Kayaking is one of the activities that I heard it won't be allowed anymore as of April 1, 2017). Kayaking is also one the 3 or 4 activities that you can do in Halong Bay. The other activities being relaxing, sightseeing, visiting the beach or the cave with the rest of the 100s tourists or swimming in the dirty water along the dead fish and jellyfish. Anyways, we were taken to a spot full of trash to kayak; of course from the boat we didn't realize that until we were in the water, rowing in the midst of plastic bags, litter, vodka bottles and dead fish at the surface. Our guide and the cruise crew did not think of taking us to a cleaner sport until later, our experience was totally ruined by what we had seen earlier. It appeared later that there is one company controlling the bay and every activity is scheduled by the minute. As a tourist you won't have a flexibility of visiting the one and only beach that is visited 100s of tourists who can only enjoy sunbathing, swimming or playing volley ball for one hour only. Reason being you need to get tickets to access the beach, and these tickets need to be bought from the mainland. So in case your wanted to visit the beach a second time during your stay at Halong bay, you may as well forget asking your guide or the ticketing office. We saw some tourists enjoy a little excitement with the speedboat, we asked our guide if we can hire one and he replied "NO Speedboat" . Why? he replied: Speedboat only for Chinese. WTF?!!!!
We were given orders to shower, drink our tea and relax on the deck.....enjoy some more sightseeing.
Honestly I wouldn't recommend Halong bay. Especially that the trip form Hanoi take 4 hours by bus, you may as well enjoy the pictures you can find on the internet and find another attraction that is less crowded and less controlled if you need some freedom while you stay.
Written April 1, 2017
Lee S
Colchester, VT1,120 contributions
5.0 of 5 bubbles
Breathtaking and Awe-inspiring
Nov 2016 ‚Ä¢ Friends
We visited Halong Bay in in mid-November, and it was a perfect time to experience this wonderful place. Crowds were very light and the bay was not choked with tour boats.
From looking out on the bay at sunset from the roof of our hotel, to cruising among its nearly 2000 islands under a blue sky, there is nothing about this place that doesn't take your breath away.
The limestone islands are a maze that offers an array of dazzling perspectives as they stack upon each other into the hazy distance, sometimes covered in a green rolling carpet of foliage and sometimes jutting out with craggy tendrils plunging into the waters. It feels like you are in the middle of a fairy tale or The Lord Of The Rings being in Halong Bay.
If your captain tries to stay apart from the majority of other charter boats, it can feel like you have the whole place to yourself, adding to the magic. Cruising Halong Bay was my single favorite activity of our entire Vietnam trip. We were lucky to have light crowds and a clear sky to make our time here and the resulting photos much better. If you are in northern Vietnam you should not miss Halong Bay.
Written January 9, 2017
ThincTravels
Alexandria, VA134 contributions
Magical Halong Bay Fishing Village Tour
Oct 2016 ‚Ä¢ Solo
This was one of the most serene parts of my experience in Vietnam. I climbed aboard a fishing boat with 3 (attractive & fun) male strangers and joined our female captain. She stood barefoot and gloveless in the boat while she silently and expertly rowed us through this immensely beautiful and virtually untouched UNESCO Heritage Site. She also gave us each hats to protect us from the hot sun, a particularly kind gesture.
We were each filled with awe and wonder... It was simply amazing and felt so magical. I wished it was a place I could live. No actually lives there nowadays.
Tips were not mentioned. Nevertheless, I felt one was well deserved for our captain. I slipped her one with a fresh pack of sugar free gum. I was so appreciative for the experience that I would have given her a bouquet of flowers and a hug too!
This was an excursion offered by the Huong Hai Sealife junk boat I was aboard (details & pics in a separate review). This fishing village tour was amazing. It can help melt away stress, lower blood pressure, bring smiles to your lips and help forget any troubles on your mind or in your heart. This is not a really quick tour. You have ample time to relax and enjoy. *Remember to bring your camera for this wonderful tour. I highly recommend it!
